> Not under soft assertions but [`satisfiesAnyOf`](https://www.javadoc.io/static/org.assertj/assertj-core/4.0.0-M1/org.assertj.core/org/assertj/core/api/AbstractAssert.html#satisfiesAnyOf(org.assertj.core.api.ThrowingConsumer...)) might be an option if you have a root instance. 
> Would that fit your use case?

Thank you for your response, I saw this as an option but it does not actually fit my case. As in my case, there is no single entity and the actual result for both the assertion does not belong to a single entity so i cannot use `satisfiesAnyof` unfotunately.

This below is the concrete example that I wish to achieve so that test passes if any of the assertion is passed. 

```java
SoftAssertions.assertSoftly(sa -> {
        sa.assertThat(isFastest).as("Fastest route").isFalse(); 
        sa.assertThat(isShortest).as("Shortest route").isFalse();
});

```

@itkhanz I'm not entirely sure the feature you're proposing has a strong connection with soft assertions.

What if we provided a new entry point in `Assertions`, like `assertAny(Runnable...)` or `assertAnyOf(Runnable...)`, which would pass only if at least one of the provided `Runnable` doesn't fail?

We probably want to define something like the JUnit [`Executable`](https://junit.org/junit5/docs/5.12.0/api/org.junit.jupiter.api/org/junit/jupiter/api/function/Executable.html) instead of `Runnable` so that the provided code has more freedom for exception throwing.

@alihmzyv sure, this is up for grabs.

@joel-costigliola any preference between `assertAny(Runnable...)` and `assertAnyOf(Runnable...)`?

In case we go with `assertAny`, I'd keep `satisfiesAnyOf` aligned, i.e., dropping the `Of` suffix
